@node "About" "About DFDKeep"
 Displays program completion date, author name address, voice & email
 phone numbers, and your registration number.

 In the UnRegistered version this About requester will pop up from time
 to time, with a very annoying "pause", to remind you to register.

 No options or features are disabled in the unregistered version. The
 only difference in the Registered version is the only time you see the
 About requester is when you select it.

 The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-A.
@endnode
@node "Info" "Information"
  Displays name of input mail file, total size of input file in bytes,
 current position of input file, output filename, size in bytes and
 number of messages kept.
 Shows the ON/OFF state of the Twit Filter, and twit definition(s) if
 there are any. Shows the ON/OFF state of the Search Filter, and its
 definition(s) if any.

 The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-? , or ? , or  i  (lower case)
@endnode
@node "Load" "Load a file"
 Pops up an ASL file requester to select a new input mail file to load.

 After choosing an input file another file requester will pop up asking
 for the output filename. This will default to "<input_file>.kpt"

 After choosing the output file the main DFDKeep window will open, then
 a ListView to choose the "Beginning of Message Key".

o You can edit the "Keys" file by loading "ENV:DFD/DFDKeep.keys" into your
o favorite text editor. The "key" characters must be the first thing on the
o line, followed by one or more spaces then the "Comment".
o
o If your startup is the (goofy) C= one that assigns ENV: to RAM: then
o copies ENVARC: to RAM:ENV - then you will need to copy the edited
o DFDKeep.keys file from ENV:DFD/ to ENVARC:DFD/ (ok I guess for floppy
o systems?) But if you've got a hard drive then do yourself a favor and
o assign ENV: to the hard drive somewhere. (mine is in S:ENV/)

 The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-L , or  L  (upper case)
@endnode
@node "Quit" "Quit"
 Close any open files and exit DFDKeep.

 On exit the following data will be saved to files in ENV:DFD/ and
 ENVARC:DFD/

 o Current Input filename and position in file. If you reload the same
    file the next time you use DFDKeep, it will be started on the last
    message displayed in the previous session.

 o  Path you chose in the Input File requester. Next time you use DFDKeep
    the Load requester will default to this directory.

 o  Path you chose in the Output File requester. Next time you use DFDKeep
    the Save requester will default to this directory.

 o  DFDKeep window position on Workbench.

 o  Search keys.

 o  Twit keys.

 o  Voice ON/OFF state.

 o  Slow voice ON/OFF state.

  The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-Q , or  Q  (upper case), or click
 the close gadget in the upper-left corner.
@endnode
@node "Search_A" "Search by keyword - Automatic"
 Pops up a string requester. Enter the text string(s) you wish to search
 for. The Search is NOT CASE SENSITIVE. If there is any match in the
 message header or body text, the message will be saved to the "kept"
 output file.

 The Search will accept up to five (5) search strings, seperated by a |
 (shifted \\). Examples;

 Amiga                           ;search for "amiga".

 amiga|duck                      ;search for "amiga" and "duck".

 demo|jazz|foobar|amiga|escom    ;search for "demo", "jazz", "foobar",
                                  "amiga", and "escom".

 You can use the Search function at any time. If you just loaded an input
 file or if you have already Skip/Kept through the file and are in the
 middle somewhere.

 To abort the Search requester press RETURN without entering any text.

  The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-S.
@endnode

@node "Search_I" "Search by keyword - Interactive"
 Turns Interactive Search mode ON/OFF.  When turned ON it pops up a string
 requester. Enter the text string(s) you wish to search for. The Search is
 NOT CASE SENSITIVE. If there is any match in the message header or body
 text, the message will be displayed, allowing you to Skip or Keep the
 found message.

 The Search will accept up to five (5) search strings, seperated by a |
 (shifted \\). Examples;

 Amiga                           ;search for "amiga".

 amiga|duck                      ;search for "amiga" and "duck".

 demo|jazz|foobar|amiga|escom    ;search for "demo", "jazz", "foobar",
                                  "amiga", and "escom".

 You can use the Search function at any time. If you just loaded an input
 file or if you have already Skip/Kept through the file and are in the
 middle somewhere. If you "Skip" a found message, you have one chance to
 go back by clicking the "<" gadget, then "Keep" it.

  To abort the Search requester press RETURN without entering any text.

  You can turn Interactive Search mode OFF by selecting the menu option
 again. A checkmark next to this menu item indicates it is ON.

  The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-I.
@endnode
@node "Twit" "Twit Filter"
 Toggles the Twit Filter state ON/OFF. A check mark next to this menu entry
 indicates it is ON. If you turn the Twit ON and have no twit filter
 definitions, the Define Twit string requester will pop up.

 The Twit Filter works in normal mode as well as both search modes.
@endnode
@node "Define" "Define Twit"
  Pops up a string requester. Enter the text string(s) you wish to filter.
 The filter is NOT CASE SENSITIVE. If there is any match in the message
 header or body text, the message will not be displayed.
  
 The Filter will accept up to ten (10) search strings, seperated by a |
 (shifted \\). Examples;

 Ibm                           ;skip messages containing "ibm".

 ibm|duck                      ;skip messages containing "ibm" or "duck".
                                  

 demo|jazz|foobar|msdos|apple  ;skip messages containing "demo", "jazz",
                                  "foobar", "msdos", or "apple".

 You can use the Twit Filter at any time. If you just loaded an input
 file or if you have already Skip/Kept through the file and are in the
 middle somewhere.

 To abort the Define requester press RETURN without entering any text.

  The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-D.
@endnode

@node "Keyboard" "Keyboard Shortcuts"
 Pops up a requester displaying the keyboard shortcuts.

 L         = Load
 Q         = Quit
 l, ,      = Less
 m, .      = More
 s, SPACE  = Skip
 k, CR     = Keep
 <, b      = Back
 ?, i      = Info
 h         = Help

  The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-H , or h  (lower case).
@endnode

@node "Voice" "Voice Toggle"
  Turns Amiga speach ON/OFF. When voice is ON DFDKeep will "read" your
 mail to you.

 The keyboard shortcut is Right-Amiga-V
@endnode
@node "Slow" "Slow Voice"
  Turning this on will cause DFDKeep to add a 5-jiffy pause (1/10th second)
 between each word and at the end of each line.

  If you have trouble understanding the slurred crappy Amiga speach
 synthesis, try turning this ON - it helps a little.
@endnode

@node "Interface" "User Interface"

           @{" Load " link "Load"} @{" Quit " link "Quit"}   @{" Less " link "Less"} @{" More " link "More"}   @{" Skip " link "Skip"} @{" Keep " link "Keep"} @{" < " link "Back1"} @{" ? " link "Info"}

@endnode
@node "Less" "Less"
 This gadget will become active if you have used the More gadget. It will
 take you back to the top of the current message.

 The keyboard shortcut is  l  (lower case)
@endnode
@node "More" "More"
 This gadget will become active if the current message will not fit in
 one window. It is a "Page Forward" function.

 The keyboard shortcut is  m  (lower case)
@endnode
@node "Skip" "Skip Message"
 This gadget tells DFDKeep you do NOT want to save the current message to
 the output file.

 The keyboard shortcut is  s  (lower case), or press SPACE.
@endnode
@node "Keep" "Keep Message"
 This gadget tells DFDKeep you WANT to save the current message to the
 output file.

 The keyboard shortcut is  k  (lower case), or press RETURN.
@endnode
@node "Back1" "Go Back 1 Message"
 This gadget will redisplay the last message.

 This only works if the last message was "Skip"ped.

 The keyboard shortcut is  < , or  b  (lower case).
@endnode

@node "History" "DFDKeep History"
 DFDKeep v1.2a (23 Mar 96);
  Twit & Search string requesters are now active when they pop up, so you
   don't have to click into them before entering text.
  About & Info requesters now have one button instead of 2.
  If DFDKeep loads the apig.library it will be expunged on exit. If it was
   already loaded when DFDKeep is run, it will not be removed from memory.
  Added keyboard shortcuts and "Keyboard Help" requester.
  Added "Realy Quit?" requester when quitting.
  Added Search mode and messages kept to "Info" requester.
  Interactive Search mode can now be turned back OFF.
  Added Voice.  Saves ON/OFF states to prefs file on exit.
  Added Slow Voice - what a kludge!
  Fixed bug in Twit. Will now override a message found by Search, and it
   will not be shown.
  Now saves Twit and Search strings to prefs file on exit.

 DFDKeep v1.2  (26 Dec 95);
  Added Twit Filter.
  Fixed bug, somtimes messages would not start displaying at their top.
   Usually after < going back 1 message.
  Cleaned up some of the code. Fixed a few errors... don't remember what
   they were though.

 DFDKeep v1.1  (25 Jul 95);
   Fixed bug that didn't CLOSE output file before loading another input
   file.
   Writes input filename, date and time to top of output file.
   Added "Interactive Search" mode.
   Search modes can now use up to 5 keywords.
   Fixed incorrect input file "Current bytes" display on "Info" requester.
   Added output file size in "Info" requester.
   Added gadget to pop up "Info" requester.
   (apparently never made it to aminet, even though I uploaded it - must
    have ended up in their bit-bucket)

 DFDKeep v1.0a (02 Jul 95);
   Wasn't creating ENV:DFD/ directory, and crashed because it couldn't
   find the DFDKeep.keys file. I never figured why the v1.0 code wouldn't
   work as it was..., but I rewrote that part and it works now.
   (apparently never made it to aminet, even though I uploaded it - must
    have ended up in their bit-bucket)

 DFDKeep v1.0  (28 Jun 95); First public release.
@endnode

